Devices to track people are increasingly demanded by parents who want to monitor their children.
Fear for their children leads more and more people to think about watching them through a GPS.
The system, set up at the beginning to search for cars can also be used to trace the movement of people and help in some cases as by exmple that of the little Anicka Janatkova.
The instrument is currently as big as a lightbox but will soon be the size of a clock.
The case of the little Anicka excited a large number of people and they began to look for ways to better protect their children.
Even if the price is to trouble their privacy.
“We strive to tell everyone that it’s not spying but just another way to reduce the likelihood of another tragedy,” says Petr Pilin from the company MAcro Weil who is one of the suppliers of tracking devices on the Czech market.
“I admit that there may be cases of poor use of such devices, such as putting it in the bag of a person who is unknown, but I have not yet met such cases.”
“Most people are customers who actually buy the product for security reasons, adds Pilin.
According to him, children should always know for what purposes the "box" is used and how to use it in emergency.
The child psychologist, Dana Bockova, draws the attention that if the child does not want to carry on him something of this kind, he will get rid of it.
“And even the smallest can show great creativity when it comes to deliberately getting rid of something when they don’t want to be under control.”
“Mobile phones, which can cut off like these tracking devices, have already brought parents to long expectations,” Bockova says.
According to her, the fact that this type of device can help in case of aggression is very controversial.
“If it’s a prepared rape, the author will do everything to ensure the child has no electronic device that can locate it.”
“Today it’s the phone.”
“As soon as the tracking devices develop, they (criminals) will search for them as the sale will be supported by a advertising campaign.”
“In such cases, criminals will always be ahead of the police,” says the psychologist.
She still acknowledges that such devices can help in an unprepared aggression by a pedophile.
According to Robert Cech of the company RC Monitoring, which offers tracking services for both cars and people, claims that having this type of device can help, even if it is destroyed in case of an aggression.
"The device can be set up in such a way that it is in regular emission after a certain period of time."
"In the event that the device is destroyed, it remains the last position of the person concerned."
“The more expensive devices also have an inclinometer that immediately signals the position of the person who has slept and is in a laying position without moving,” Cech says.
According to him, so-called smart phones that are equipped with a navigation system, can offer a comparable service after having formated it with a special prologue.
The problem with the current tracking systems is that it is either a device similar to those we carry in pendentif of the size of a lightbox or to the smallest telephone devices.
You can always lose them.
According to Pilina of Macro Weil, this is why tests are currently being carried out to make devices that look like common digital clocks.
"This will have the advantage that the potential aggressor will not be able to recognize the tracking device."
"Of he will realize it after a certain time, which will give the police a little more time," he added.
Whether the tracking device is developed in the form of a bracelet or a pendentif, it will always use the same technology as for tracking cars.
This is a combination of position acquisition systems using the GPS (which is commonly used in self-navigation) and a cell phone function that alerts the current position of a vehicle.
