An index longer than the annular is a sign of low risk of cancer
Men who have the index longer than the annular are exposed to a lower risk of developing prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published on Wednesday by the British magazine Cancer.
This may depend on the level of the male hormone testosterone.
“Our findings show that the relative length of the finger serves as a simple test of prostate cancer risk, especially for men before the age of 60,” said Ros Eeles, co-author of the study, professor at the Institute for Cancer Research at the University of Warwick.
The finger could thus help to determine which men should submit to the prostate cancer test, including by combining with genetic risk or other aggravating factors such as family health backgrounds.
During the period 1994-2009 she followed with colleagues in Britain more than 1,500 patients with prostate cancer and at the same time three thousand healthy men.
More than half of the participants in the study had the right hand index shorter than the annular.
For them as for the 19 percent of those who had the fingers of the same length, the same probability of a prostate cancer was found.
In the case of those who had the index longer than the annular risk, however, fell to 33 percent, for men before the age of 60 the risk decrease reached 87 percent.
The length ratio of the two fingers mentioned - formed during the prenatal period - indicates in particular different levels of sexual hormones to which the child is exposed in the uterus.
Less testosterone corresponds to a longer index.
Previous research has shown that it is just testosterone that helps to develop prostate cancer.
Professor Vacla Paces, a renowned Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences, told CTK that he is aware of this study but that he doesn’t seem, it seems, that the relationship between finger length and cancer is “fullly demonstrated”.
