A microbe that tolerates arsenic raises the possibility of new types of life on Earth, or elsewhere.
The discovery of a strange bacteria, which can use arsenic as one of its nutrients, expands the field to find new forms of life on Earth and beyond.
Although researchers have discovered the unusual bacteria here on Earth, they say that this shows that life has possibilities beyond the major elements that have been considered essential.
“This body has a double capacity.”
“It can be developed either with phosphorus or with arsenic.”
"It's why it's very special, even though it's far from being a really 'strange' form of life," commented Paul Davies C. W. of Arizona State University, co-author of the report appearing in the Thursday online edition of the journal Science.
Six major elements have long been considered essential for life: carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulfur.
But researchers found that the bacteria, discovered in Lake Mono, California, is able to continue to develop after replacing phosphorus with arsenic.
“We’re wondering what’s still possible,” said Ariel Anbar D. of Arizona State University, co-author of the report.
Discovery is important in the field of life research beyond the Earth because researchers must be able to recognize life, to know what life looks like, says Anbar.
The study focuses on a microbe found on Earth.
However, the announcement of a press conference to discuss it, which did not disclose the details of the discovery, generated widespread speculation on the Internet that the report could disclose the discovery of an alien life.
This was not the case.
The discovery “mosts that, in other planetary environments, organisms could be able to use other elements to activate biochemistry and that the “standard” set of elements, which we consider absolutely necessary for life, could not be fixed,” commented Charles Cockell, professor at the Institute of Planetary and Space Scientific Research, Open University, Milton Keynes, UK.
Cockell was not part of the research team.
"This work is new because it shows the replacement of one element to another in basic biochemistry and biochemical structure," added Cockell.
It was not a random discovery.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of NASA's Institute of Astrology, who led the study, chose Lake Mono because it has high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are chemically similar; thus, it speculated that a microbe exposed to both substances could be able to replace each other.
“Arsenic is toxic mainly because its chemical behavior is really similar to that of phosphorus.”
"As a result, organisms have difficulty distinguishing these elements separately."
"But arsenic is different enough so that it doesn't work exactly like phosphorus; it penetrates inside and somehow gums the work of our biochemical machine," Anbar explained.
The researchers collected the bacteria known as GFAJ-1 and exposed it to increasing concentrations of arsenic to which it was able to adapt and grow.
The microbe grows better with phosphorus but the fact that it can live with arsenic instead raises the possibility that a form of life using arsenic can occur naturally, either elsewhere on Earth or on another planet or moon where arsenic is more common.
Jamie S. Foster, adjunct professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, said that the idea that arsenic could be replaced by phosphorus was not new; but nothing ever showed that it could work.
Arsenic was more common at the beginning of Earth’s existence, she says; thus, the researchers issued the hypothesis that the first forms of life could have used it.
This suggests that there may be other ways to form life, not just the way life on Earth was formed at the beginning,” said Foster, who was not part of Wolfe-Simon’s research team.
The research was funded by NASA, the Ministry of Energy and the National Institute of Health.
