A Global Plan to Restore Lighting
The UN proposed a plan to renew domestic, commercial and industrial lighting in 100 countries in order to a reduction in greenhouse gases (GES) which corresponds to almost a third of the additional reduction to be achieved to stabilize the global climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan lies in the footsteps of the major concrete projects that the UN hopes to adopt in Cancun to compensate for the lack of compulsory reduction commitments by the industrialized countries.
According to the plan submitted yesterday, if the incandescent lamps that still monopolize 50 to 70% of the market were replaced by fluocompact lamps or, better, by electroluminescent diod lamps (DEL or "LED" in English), the majority of the 1.8 billion tons (Gt) of GES emitted to lighting humans would be avoided.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
This is the equivalent of 70% of the emissions of the global car park.
In Copenhagen last year, major emitter countries, such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, engaged in voluntary reduction plans that are expected to increase global GES emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
But it will need to be removed from this balance even 5 Gt to be able to stabilize the climate rise to 2 degrees Celsius by 2020 in order to prevent it from becoming out of control.
In incandescent lamps, 95% of energy is dispersed in the form of heat and the rest, or 5%, is produced by light.
With fluocompact lamps, energy consumption is reduced by 75% and with new DEL lamps, this energy need is reduced twice again.
Fluocompact lamps last on average between 6000 and 10,000 hours.
The new DEL lamps, like those launched by the manufacturer Philips this week – this company has also participated in the UN study – have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than an incandescent lamp, giving an idea of the possible economy with a replacement plan that would apply to 100 countries.
These all new lamps can also work with reostates in addition to emitting very little heat.
They do not contain mercury.
Several specialists have shown reserves in the place of fluocompact lamps as they contain mercury and that they must be removed as dangerous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries, unless manufacturers put instructions.
But, the report indicates, the main source of mercury emission on the planet is not the fluocompact lamp, but rather the coal thermal power plants, which emit a lot of mercury to produce the electricity spent in incandescent lamps.
Only in the United States, these power plants emit 25,000 tons of mercury per year.
The report details the gains that each country would make through this international program.
For example, Indonesia would save one billion dollars a year on electricity and eight million tons of CO2, which is equivalent to 3.5 thermal power plants whose construction would cost it 2.5 billion dollars.
