Climate: How France Sweeps its Financing Promises
A year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it’s time to examine the fulfilment of promises of rapidly unlocked financing (the so-called fast-start or early financing) made by developed countries.
And the great French shadows are revealed.
In the Copenhagen Agreement, developed countries have pledged to provide $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union has promised €7.2 billion over three years and France €1.26 billion (or €420 million per year).
At the opening of the COP16, the EU made the big game to convince its partners of the reality of its commitment to fast-start financing: a detailed report on the action of its Member States, a press conference, a big side event, brochure distribution...
The transparency operation is valuable and appreciated at its fair value: developing countries and civil society would like all developed countries to do the same with the same level of accuracy.
The EU announces that it has delivered €2.2 billion in 2010, putting it on the right way to fulfill its €7.2 billion commitment in 2012.
But when you look in detail, things are more complicated.
This money must, according to the Copenhagen Agreement, be "new and additional" in order to ensure that additional efforts are made without being at the expense of the Public Development Aid.
Unfortunately, there is no agreement on what "new and additional" means.
While the European Commission had proposed a harmonisation, some Member States whose France blocked the procedure.
Today, everyone chooses the reference that best suits him.
For example, the European Commission has regarded 2009 as a reference year: international funding isined, and it adds 150 million over three years in the framework of fast-start funding.
Other countries have chosen similar references in terms of year or level of public development aid.
France, on the contrary, estimates that the financing of "all new projects" in 2010 is "new and additional".
In other words, there is no reference to the expenditure of the previous years or the overall level of Public Development Aid.
Concretely, the total amount of France’s support to developing countries can remain stable (or even decrease), it claims to respect its commitment to “new and additional” financing.
Another key element is the distribution between donations and loans.
There is no rule and everyone chooses his way of calculation.
Some, like France, consider that 1 € borrowed is equivalent to 1 € given.
Of course, this is hardly justifiable: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans can be justified for certain profitable investments (sometimes projects related to emission mitigation based on more efficient technologies), it is false to present an euro that will be recovered as equivalent to an euro that is given...
But France has only to do such a reasoning: it “respect” its commitment of 420 million euros by making 91.5% loans (389.8 million euros) and 8.5% donations (36.1 million euros) – see the EU document to check by yourself.
It is the only country in the EU to use the loan so massively.
Germany requires 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (in other countries) comply with their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the very large majority of the European Union puts 1€ to meet its commitment, France puts only 10 cents and considers the effort comparable.
Beautiful passport tour!
In short, in its fast start financing, France operates a double fraud: on the one hand on the evolution of action in time and on the other hand on the reality of the financial effort.
By spending only €36.1 million, it can make it believed that it spends €420 million "new and additional" in consistency with its promises.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems good that it was Bercy who made the arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why would other Member States continue to give if it was enough to borrow?) and in negotiations since developing countries are not completely deceived...
The early financing chapter is just a small, relatively short-term issue, compared to all the climate discussions.
But it could be a more sand grain in the enormous machine that is the UNFCCC.
We hope that this will not be the case.
In any case, it is essential to get the lessons from this first year of early financing.
First of all, France could announce a change in its accounting mode for the years 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of respect for its commitments and equity with the other countries of the European Union.
But most importantly, France could advance the discussions on the long-term financing issues (an other crucial chapter currently discussed): we will not escape the question of "additionality" or how to account for loans.
France could change its position to become as progressive on these issues as it is on others.
The hope is therefore based on the new Environment Minister, Ms Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprising announcement on France’s fast start and its vision of “additionality” and the use of loans would increase the level of international trust needed to advance in the discussions.
