The association, which warns that its results “do not have significant statistical value in view of the small number of samples analyzed, but are illustrative of the problematics treated,” bought between July and September the foods generally consumed in four meals and an incas in a day by a child of a decade, in the supermarkets of Oise and Paris.
These typical meals, including the official recommendations - five fresh fruits and vegetables, three dairy products and 1.5 liters of water per day - as well as sweets, have been examined by laboratories searching for chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other pollutants.
The balance of the plate is overwhelming: 81 chemicals of which 42 are classified as possible or likely cancerogenic and five classified as certain cancerogenic as well as 37 substances likely to act as endocrine disruptors (PE), according to studies from several institutions such as the International Center for Cancer Research.
“While, in almost all cases, the legal limits for each chemical taken individually are not exceeded, we see well in our survey that the reality of consumers’ exposure to potentially cancer-genic contaminants and/or PE is worrying,” the association notes.
For breakfast, butter and milk tea alone contain more than a dozen possible cancerous residues and three proven to be certain cancerous as well as twenty residues likely to disrupt the hormonal system.
The apple, which is imported from Brazil, has traces of six chemicals, one of which is forbidden in France.
The same for Kenya’s green beans, included in lunch, on which the study found traces of a powerful insecticide banned in the EU.
In addition, the steak, the box tuna, and even the bread bag and the chewing gum were filled with pesticides and other chemicals.
In the water of the rubber the analyses revealed the presence of nitrates and chlorform.
For dinner, the salmon steak was the most "rich" with 34 chemical remains detected and even the examination of the plastic plate used to heat the microwave meal was not exempt.
The final risk for the consumer of this “contaminant cocktails” is “probably underestimated”, according to the study.
The Alliance Europe Ecology-The Greens (EE-LV), on its side, proposed "face to the emergency of the situation" to establish a moratorium on the use of pesticides, in order to stop "the increase of diseases of civilization".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Agency (EFSA) the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruits and vegetables consumed in Europe, 76 of which in cereals.
